Skeleton
(
Fig. 2C
). There is not clear distinction between the ectosome and the choanosome. Dichotriaenes with cladome tangential to the surface are detectable in the ectosome which is cut across by bundles of oxeas (
Fig. 2C
). Oxeas and triaenes are rather disorderly arranged in the choanosome. Microscleres are scattered through the whole sponge body without a superficial concentration.

Spirasters are the most abundant microscleres and may be tentatively separated into three different types . Type I ( Fig. 3G ): long and rather straight axis (22.5 (28.7) 42.5 µm long) with short, conical, spiny rays 2.5 µm long. Type II ( Fig. 3H ): rather short, twisted axis (17.5 (24) 30 µm long) with conical spiny rays longer (5 (6.3) 7.5 µm ) than in type I. Type III (
Fig. 3I
): intermediate between metaster and spiraster, with rather short twisted axis (15 (17.7) 25 µm long) and cylindrical spiny rays about 5 µm long. Plesiasters ( Fig. 3J ) 37.5 (51.7) 80 µm long with entirely spiny rays 15 (20.5) 25 µm long.
